#TWFT52 WEEK 21 – Swipe for starter questions and my own response (also at link in profile).
@thewordforthis
✒🖤
• 
The Word for This is “THINK”
• 
Trapped amid wavy
quavering mirrors, bouncing 
ideas between warped
reflective surfaces, distorting
themselves, recording in cells
and bolts of electricity (invisible
to the eye) reinforcing, sly,
jolting me from any errant
moment of safety;
the current flow crackling
steady, threatening to
arc free: is there something in
this life for me?
• 
I debated whether to revise the last line, so I want to clarify its meaning: this is not a reference to self-harm or suicide. I’d tell you if it was.
• 
When I saw which of my randomized words was assigned to week 21, I almost laughed. Think. I do little else. Easy one, right? Maybe. Maybe not. When your first image is funhouse mirrors, it’s *possible* that what’s going on in there is challenging.
• 
I understand intellectually that my mental wiring, not only the parts of my brain that run various parts and systems, but the mysterious alchemy of thought, isn’t serving me. I’ve talked through these patterns and belief systems (as biological and real as the ones that run my heart, my lungs, the organs that sustain this machine of me) for enough years that I can identify them. I can stare them down, chart the place where reflection bends an idea into a shape it was never meant to hold. I understand what they’ve kept from me, what they’ve kept me from. I even understand that they’re not fixed, that they can change, that I can change them.
• 
Intellectually.
• 
I’m facing a potential new reality that could change a lot for me; not everything, but enough that life may look noticeably different. (I can’t be any more transparent than that right now, but I promise to share if and when I know more.)
• 
And the part I have to prepare for most isn’t the external change. It’s how I think about myself. How I think about my Self.

How easy it is for us to hide behind our intellect instead of allowing the professionals to guide us into a better way of thinking. How easy it is to  tell everyone “What” we need and “How” we need to get it. How easy it is for us to think that by “helping” (saving) another person we are unselfishly helping our fellow humans but in fact we are delving into the addiction of codependency. How easy it is for us to replicate the abuse and neglect in all of our relationships thinking that it is all we deserve. How easy it is to do what we need to to not think...but in turn managing to motivate the brain into overdrive. The only thing I know for sure is that there is a long way from the head to the heart but by doing what needs to be done and “GOING” through it to “GET” through it is the only way to bridge the gap between the two. This is the truth. I think...

@megs921 That first sentence is a *perfect* summary of... ME. I don't even realize I'm doing it most of the time, until I encounter someone willing and able to call me on it. It's all part of underlying control issues, and while it's progress that I no longer get defensive (I usually just end up laughing at myself, in that rueful SMDH sort of way), I still have so much rewiring to do. Codependency plays a role in all of this too, for sure, though I've been able to unlearn a lot of it maintain that loving detachment more and more. Not always, but more. Thank you for articulating this so beautifully. ✒🖤

@thewordforthis I agree with all. I was in a group therapy program many years ago and I was called out on this behavior in extreme ways that still stick with me. First, the therapist called me “Meg I know,” I had ALL of the answers not just for me but for all of my peers. I would call out, barge in and interrupt other people’s sharing to remind them how “brilliant” I was and to tell them what my be all/end all to their issue must be. My therapist got so annoyed she made me pull up and tie the hood on my hoodie and sit with a notepad on my lap to write down any thoughts I might have. I did that for five sessions. I became aware-certainly not perfect but aware of my rude behavior. We boiled it down to my upbringing in a very loud family where everyone spoke over each other and you had to fight to get your voice heard. Makes total sense. I began practicing active listening and still to this day use that hoodie as an anchoring tool.
@thewordforthis Also-control, codependency and for me ACOA issues all play a major part.

I think I overthink, actually I know I do.  Anxiety and ptsd, will do that to a person. But over time and with some practice the thoughts that play havoc with your most protected space of your mind can be eased when you can understand the root of circumstance.
@solace_in_chaos_memoir "... the root of circumstance" is so on point. ✒🖤
“Where the mind goes the man follows “
